04034nam a22005535i 9780520975736DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021056653  a9780520975736  a(DE-B1597)627313  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aN7832b.J455 2022 4aN7832b.J455 2022 7aREL0700002bisacsh04a246/.2223/eng/202204061 aJensen, Robin M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Idols to Icons :bThe Emergence of Christian Devotional Images in Late Antiquity /cRobin M. Jensen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChristianity in Late Antiquity ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1. Early Christian Condemnation of Idols -- t2. Aniconism: In Defense of the Invisible God -- t3. Epiphanies: Encountering the Visible God -- t4. Early Christian Pictorial Art: From Sacred Narratives to Holy Portraits -- t5. Holy Portraits: Controversies and Commendation -- t6. The True Likeness -- t7. Miraculous and Mediating Portraits -- t8. Materiality, Visuality, and Spiritual Insight -- tEpilogue: The Idols’ Last Stand -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven the briefest glance at an art museum’s holdings or an introductory history textbook demonstrates the profound influence of Christian images and art. From Idols to Icons tells the fascinating history of the dramatic shift in Christian attitudes toward sacred images from the third through the early seventh century. From attacks on the cult images of polytheism to the emergence of Christian narrative iconography to the appearance of portrait-type representations of holy figures, this book examines the primary theological critiques and defenses of holy images in light of the surviving material evidence for early Christian visual art. Against the previous assumption that fourth- and fifth-century Christians simply forgot or ignored their predecessors’ censure and reverted to more alluring pagan practices, Robin M. Jensen contends that each stage of this profound change was uniquely Christian. Through a careful consideration of the cults of saints’ remains, devotional portraits, and pilgrimages to sacred sites, Jensen shows how the Christian devotion to holy images came to be rooted in their evolving conviction that the divine was accessible in and through visible objects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArt, Early Christian. 0aChristian art and symbolismyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aImage of God. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975736/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY